{"questionId":"5274681","questionHtml":"<p>Which combination describes an electrolytic cell?<br><br></p>\n<table style=\"height:180px;width:395.632px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26px;\">&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:186px;\"><strong>Energy change</strong></td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:165.632px;\"><strong>Spontaneity</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26px;\">A.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:186px;\">chemical to electrical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:165.632px;\">non-spontaneous</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26px;\">B.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:186px;\">electrical to chemical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:165.632px;\">non-spontaneous</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26px;\">C.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:186px;\">chemical to electrical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:165.632px;\">spontaneous</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width:26px;\">D.&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:186px;\">electrical to chemical</td>\n<td style=\"text-align:center;width:165.632px;\">spontaneous</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","markschemeHtml":"<p>B</p>","meta":{"questionId":"5274681","referenceCode":"23M.1.HL.TZ1.29","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Which combination describes an electrolytic cell? Energy change Spontaneity A. chemical to electrical non-spontaneous B. electrical to chemical non-spontaneous C. chemical to elect","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"29","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 12: Atomic structure","12.1 Electrons in atoms","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 12: Atomic structure"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}